---
name: legate.unwedge
description: "Mini-legate's skill for unwedging hatchery dispatch failures that left behind stale local branches or revealed partial-work scenarios. Use when the deterministic loop sends a [PROCESSOR] request with reason starting with 'hatchery_dispatch_failed' or 'branch-collision', or when `march herald state --json` shows a slice escalated with escalatedReason 'hatchery_dispatch_failed'. Inspects the colliding branch, classifies the collision (orphan-ref, post-merge-stale, open-pr, diverged-unknown), and either cleans it autonomously (deleting the local branch and requesting recovery so the loop re-dispatches) or escalates with the verdict so the operator/agent can act."
allowed-tools: Bash(.claude/skills/legate.unwedge/scripts/inspect-partial-work.sh:*) Bash(.claude/skills/legate.unwedge/scripts/clean-stale-branch.sh:*)
---

# Skill: legate.unwedge (hatchery branch-collision + partial-work recovery)

The deterministic loop now auto-recovers the most common branch-collision failures (HEAD-on-default-branch orphan refs and post-merge stale refs with no open PR), and bounded auto-recovery re-dispatches `hatchery_dispatch_failed` escalations a couple of times on its own (#211). For everything past that budget — open PRs, diverged HEADs with no PR record, the partial-work scenario where smithy keeps reporting a slice as ready even after its PR landed, or an escalation that exhausted its auto-recovery budget — the loop escalates here, because once a slice escalates with its budget spent there is no internal re-dispatch path (#238).

The loop is Herald-backed (#176): there is **no `state.json`**. Read the escalated slice from `march herald state --json`, and recover it by appending an event — never by editing a state file. `clean-stale-branch.sh` deletes the stale local branch and then runs `march legate recover <slice-id>`, which the running loop honors on its next tick (it drops the escalated slice and re-dispatches the still-ready smithy work fresh).

Load via `Skill(skill="legate.unwedge")` before invoking any script. The classifier registers the allowed-tools for the rest of the session.

---

## Triggers

Run this skill when any of these happen:

- The loop sends `[PROCESSOR]` and the newest relevant request in `legate-loop-requests.ndjson` has `reason` starting with `hatchery_dispatch_failed` or `branch-collision`.
- `march herald state --json` shows a slice with `stage: "escalated"` and `escalatedReason: "hatchery_dispatch_failed"` (the loop's auto-recovery budget for it is spent — confirm via the processor request's detail, which says so when it escalates to you).
- The operator asks you to investigate a stuck dispatch.

Do **not** run this skill for normal CI failures, merge conflicts, or review comments. Those stay in `legate.babysit`.

---

## Inputs to read

1. `march herald state --json` — locate the escalated slice by id under `.slices`. The fold carries `stage` (`escalated`), `escalatedReason` (`hatchery_dispatch_failed`), and `branch` (the symbolic dispatch branch, e.g. `smithy/forge/...`). The fold does **not** carry the smithy `command`/`arguments` — read those from the processor request (next input) and from `smithy status`.
2. `~/.agent-deck/conductor/{{LOOP_NAME}}/legate-loop-requests.ndjson` — read the latest `hatchery_dispatch_failed` / `branch-collision-*` entry for the structured detail the loop already gathered. **The actual git branch (with the `feature/` prefix agent-deck adds) is parsed from this request's detail.** Prefer that branch when inspecting / cleaning; the slice's symbolic `branch` from Herald (e.g. `smithy/forge/...`) will not match the real local ref you need to operate on.
3. The colliding branch in `{{REPO_PATH}}` — never trust a stale verdict, re-run `inspect-partial-work.sh` if any time has elapsed.

---

## Classification

The loop emits a verdict in the escalation detail (e.g. `branch-collision-open-pr`, `branch-collision-diverged-unknown`). Re-validate it with `inspect-partial-work.sh` before acting. Final classifications:

- `orphan-ref` — branch HEAD is an ancestor of the default branch (no diverged work). Loop should have auto-recovered this; if you see it here, the loop's gh/git probe failed.
- `post-merge-stale` — branch has merged PR(s) and no open PR, but HEAD isn't an ancestor of default (squash-merge). Loop should also have auto-recovered.
- `open-pr` — branch has an open PR. Escalate to operator — do not delete.
- `diverged-unknown` — branch has diverged HEAD with no PR record. Escalate.
- `partial-work` — merged PR(s) exist AND `smithy status` still reports the slice's `next_action` as ready. The PR landed incomplete; the slice needs a corrective dispatch with a custom prompt addressing the gap. This skill cannot autonomously dispatch corrective work yet (tracked separately); escalate via `NEED:` with the specific gap.

---

## Recovery Actions

### `orphan-ref` / `post-merge-stale`

The loop should have handled these autonomously. If you reach this branch, it likely failed (gh auth, network, etc.). Run the cleanup manually:

```bash
.claude/skills/legate.unwedge/scripts/clean-stale-branch.sh \
  "{{REPO_PATH}}" "<branch>" "<slice-id>"
```

The script re-validates safety conditions before acting, deletes the stale local branch, then runs `march legate recover <slice-id>` so the loop drops the escalated slice and re-dispatches the still-ready smithy work on its next tick. If it exits non-zero with `refused`, do **not** retry — classify as `open-pr` or `diverged-unknown` instead. If it exits non-zero because the recovery request itself failed (Herald unreachable), the branch is already cleaned — re-run `march legate recover <slice-id>` once Herald is back.

Record in `task-log.md`:

```markdown
## YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM — Hatchery branch unwedge
- <slice-id> branch=<branch> verdict=<verdict>; cleared + recovery requested. Loop will re-dispatch.
```

Reply `[STATUS]` with the slice id + verdict + "cleared for re-dispatch".

### `open-pr`

Do not delete. Reply:

```text
NEED: Hatchery dispatch for <slice-id> blocked by existing branch <branch> with open PR #<n> (<url>). Either land or close that PR before the loop can re-dispatch this slice. Operator action required.
```

### `diverged-unknown`

Do not delete. Run `inspect-partial-work.sh` to capture the divergence (last 5 commits, etc.) and include the report in the NEED:

```text
NEED: Hatchery dispatch for <slice-id> blocked by existing branch <branch>. HEAD has diverged from <default> with no PR record. Inspection below — operator decide whether to delete or salvage.

<paste inspect-partial-work.sh output>
```

### `partial-work`

Run `inspect-partial-work.sh` to capture the merged-PR body + diff stat, then read `smithy status --format json` for the slice's parent record to identify what's still expected. Reply:

```text
NEED: Slice <slice-id> shows partial-work signature. Merged PR(s): #<n> (<url>). Smithy still reports next_action=<command> args=<args>. Gap (best-effort summary based on merged-PR diff vs. expected scope):
- <gap line 1>
- <gap line 2>

Recommended corrective scope:
- <correction line 1>
- <correction line 2>

Autonomous corrective dispatch is not yet implemented (see march issue #<n>). Operator decide: re-dispatch same scope (run clean-stale-branch.sh and let loop retry — likely produces the same partial result), or compose a corrective prompt and spawn manually via `march hatchery spawn`.
```

---

## State Updates

There is **no `state.json`** to update (#176). The legate loop owns the slice's
working state and rebuilds it from the Herald event log; you change that state
only by appending events, never by editing a file. `clean-stale-branch.sh` already
does this for you — its `march legate recover <slice-id>` appends the
`slice.recovery.requested` event that drops the escalated slice and re-dispatches
it.

So the only record you write by hand is the operator-facing log: append a short
`task-log.md` entry as shown above (`<slice-id> branch=<branch> verdict=<verdict>;
cleared + recovery requested`). For an escalation you did **not** clean (open-pr /
diverged-unknown / partial-work), log the verdict and the `NEED:` you raised
instead.

---

## Operation Reference

| Operation | Script | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Inspect partial-work / branch collision | `inspect-partial-work.sh <repo-path> <branch>` | Read-only. Prints HEAD, ancestry, PR list, merged-PR body + diff stat. |
| Clean stale branch + request recovery | `clean-stale-branch.sh <repo-path> <branch> <slice-id>` | Refuses unless verdict is orphan-ref or post-merge-stale. Deletes the local branch, then `march legate recover <slice-id>` so the loop re-dispatches. No state file. |
| Read escalated slice state | `march herald state --json` | The Herald fold (`.slices[<id>]`): `stage`, `escalatedReason`, symbolic `branch`. |
| Request recovery directly | `march legate recover <slice-id>` | Appends `slice.recovery.requested`; the loop drops the slice + re-dispatches. Use when there is no branch to clean (e.g. a Hatchery 404). |

---

## Safety Rules

- Never delete a branch that has any open PR, regardless of what the loop's escalation detail says. Re-validate every time.
- There is no `state.json` to edit (#176). Recover only by appending the event — via `clean-stale-branch.sh` (which calls `march legate recover`) or `march legate recover <slice-id>` directly. Never reach into the loop's working state or Herald's sqlite by hand.
- Never `git push --delete` the remote branch from this skill — only delete local refs. Remote branches associated with merged PRs should be cleaned up by the PR-cleanup flow, not here.
- If `clean-stale-branch.sh` exits non-zero with `refused`, do **not** retry — read the stderr verdict and escalate. If it exits non-zero because the recovery request failed (branch already cleaned), re-run `march legate recover <slice-id>` once Herald is reachable.
- For `partial-work`, do **not** attempt to manually re-dispatch via `agent-deck session send`. A corrective spawn goes through `march hatchery spawn` and that's outside this skill's scope today; `march legate recover` only re-runs the *same* scope, which likely reproduces the partial result.
